      <div xml:id="NA44-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">iḵtu iṟceṟippiṉ piṟṟaiñāṉṟu (ET: piṟṟaiñāṉṟai) talaimakaṉ kuṟiyiṭattu vantu colliyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what HE said when coming to the place of meeting at a time when [SHE] had been confined to the house.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA44">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            poruvi lāyamō ṭaruvi yāṭi</l>
<l>            nīralaic civanta pēramar maḻaikkaṭ</l>
<l>            kuṟiyā nōkkamoṭu muṟuva ṉalki</l>
<l>            maṉaivayiṟ peyarnta kālai niṉaiiya</l>
<l>            niṉakkō vaṟiyuna ṇeñcē puṉatta </l>
<l>            nīṭilai viḷaitiṉaik koṭuṅkā ṉimirak</l>
<l>            koḻuṅkural kōṭal kaṇṇic ceḻumpala</l>
<l>            palkiḷaik kuṟava ralkayar muṉṟiṟ</l>
<l>            kuṭakkā yāciṉip paṭappai nīṭiya</l>
<l>            paṉmara vuyarciṉai miṉmiṉi viḷakkattuc </l>
<l>            ceṉmaḻai yiyakkaṅ kāṇu</l>
<l>            naṉmalai nāṭaṉ kātaṉ makaḷē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>As for you<note place="foot">There is a major construction problem in this sentence, namely <term xml:lang="ta">niṉakk-ō aṟiyunaḷ</term>. Either we have to understand <term xml:lang="ta">niṉakku</term> as a direct object of <term xml:lang="ta">aṟiyunaḷ</term>, with the only justification that T.V.G. knows of a dative coming for an accusative (he adduces KT 28.5), or we have to take <term xml:lang="ta">aṟiyunaḷ</term> as a passive ("is she known to you"), which has no morphological justification at all. A third possibility might be a sort of loose construction (as tried above), taking the -ō as a demarcation of topic ("with respect to you,"), but then the rest has to be assertion and not question.</note>,</l>
<l>who have been thinking of [her since] the time she returned to the house,</l>
<l rend="indent">having granted [you] a smile with an unintentional look from</l>
<l rend="indent2">her big, beautiful rain-eyes, reddened by water dashing against [them]</l>
<l rend="indent3">when she played in the waterfall with [her] incomparable companions,</l>
<l rend="indent4">
    <choice>
    <seg>– she is known to [you], heart,</seg>
    <seg>Does she know you, heart?</seg>
    <seg>Is she known to you, heart?</seg>
</choice> </l>
<l>the beloved daughter of the man from the land of good mountains,</l>
<l rend="indent">where the hill inhabitants with many, many(?)<note place="foot">What is the significance of <term xml:lang="ta">ceḻum pala pal kiḷai</term>? Just an enormous number? One repetition or one pair of quasi-synonyms is quite usual, but both together is odd.</note> relatives,</l>
<l rend="indent">[wearing] chaplets of white Malabar lily with rich spikes,</l>
<l rend="indent">see<note place="foot">The construction of this clause is, as usual, quite unmarked. It can also be read, with the commentary, (for example) as: "where the motion of the wandering clouds is visible in the light of the fireflies... ".</note> the motion of the falling rain</l>
<l rend="indent2">in the light of the fireflies in the high branches of many trees, reaching</l>
<l rend="indent2">into the garden of bread-fruit trees with pot[-shaped] unripe fruits</l>
<l rend="indent3">in the front yard immersed in night, while the bent stalks</l>
<l rend="indent3">of the ripening long-leaved millet stand upright in [their] fields.</l>
<lg type="alternate" sameAs="6-8b">
    <l>where the hill inhabitant with many many relatives abounding in chaplets,</l>
    <l>in the frontyards, where at night they are busy with taking the fat ears</l>
	<l>when the bent stalks of the ripening long-leaved millet stand upright in</l> 
    <l>the fields</l>
</lg>
        </lg>
         </div>
